## Empirical Evidence on Jury vs. Judge Decision-Making

Research comparing jury and judge decisions reveals nuanced findings:

| Aspect                        | Jury Trials                         | Bench Trials (Judges)                |
|------------------------------|-----------------------------------|------------------------------------|
| **Conviction/Liability Rates** | Similar overall; varies by case type | Similar overall; varies by case type |
| **Understanding of Law**       | Limited legal knowledge; guided by instructions | Expert legal knowledge             |
| **Bias and Impartiality**      | Potential for lay biases; group deliberation may mitigate | Potential for individual judicial bias |
| **Decision Consistency**       | More variability due to lay perspectives | More consistent due to legal training |
| **Speed and Efficiency**       | Generally slower and costlier     | Generally faster and cost-effective |

Studies indicate no consistent superiority of judges or juries in verdict accuracy, but differences in how cases are weighed and decided exist ([Criminal Justice, n.d.](http://criminal-justice.iresearchnet.com/forensic-psychology/jury-decisions-vs-judges-decisions/)).

